1
00:00:38,921 --> 00:00:40,921
<i>The open ocean.</i>

2
00:00:42,361 --> 00:00:46,561
<i>It covers more than half
the surface of our planet.</i>

3
00:00:46,641 --> 00:00:48,361
<i>Yet, for the most part</i>

4
00:00:48,441 --> 00:00:52,561
<i>it's a watery desert, empty of life.</i>

5
00:00:56,121 --> 00:01:00,361
<i>Hunters here spend their lives
in a constant search</i>

6
00:01:00,441 --> 00:01:03,241
<i>for scarce and elusive prey.</i>

7
00:01:17,961 --> 00:01:21,921
<i>Remarkably, this seemingly
barren wilderness</i>

8
00:01:22,001 --> 00:01:26,041
<i>is home to the largest hunter
of them all.</i>

9
00:01:30,481 --> 00:01:32,041
<i>The blue whale.</i>

10
00:01:41,761 --> 00:01:46,281
<i>Weighing 200 tonnes and 30 metres long,</i>

11
00:01:46,361 --> 00:01:50,161
<i>these are the biggest animals ever
to have lived.</i>

12
00:02:03,521 --> 00:02:06,321
<i>Despite their immense size</i>

13
00:02:06,401 --> 00:02:09,361
<i>blue whales are one of the most
streamlined</i>

14
00:02:09,441 --> 00:02:13,481
<i>and energy-efficient of all swimmers.</i>

15
00:02:23,401 --> 00:02:26,961
<i>Their food is so scarce
and widely spread</i>

16
00:02:27,041 --> 00:02:30,601
<i>that blue whales
must journey across whole oceans</i>

17
00:02:31,681 --> 00:02:34,521
<i>just to find a single meal.</i>

18
00:02:41,201 --> 00:02:46,721
<i>They can travel over a hundred miles
a day, for weeks at a time.</i>

19
00:02:59,401 --> 00:03:04,441
<i>The ocean's largest animal
feeds on one of its smallest.</i>

20
00:03:06,201 --> 00:03:09,921
<i>Krill, small shrimp-like crustaceans.</i>

21
00:03:17,121 --> 00:03:21,121
<i>Opening its gigantic mouth
takes so much effort</i>

22
00:03:21,201 --> 00:03:26,081
<i>that they only do so when the swarms
of krill are rich and concentrated.</i>

23
00:03:32,321 --> 00:03:35,361
<i>The krill here is too scattered,</i>

24
00:03:35,441 --> 00:03:37,921
<i>not even worth slowing down for.</i>

25
00:04:10,281 --> 00:04:15,721
<i>This blue whale's lonely search for food
must go on.</i>

26
00:04:22,121 --> 00:04:27,121
<i>Out here feeding opportunities
are always few and far between.</i>

27
00:04:28,601 --> 00:04:30,721
<i>And they never last long.</i>

28
00:04:36,681 --> 00:04:39,041
<i>Prey is devoured within minutes.</i>

29
00:04:49,401 --> 00:04:54,241
<i>When it's all over the hunters
must resume their endless search.</i>

30
00:04:58,321 --> 00:05:02,121
<i>Frigate birds,
the pirates of the high seas.</i>

31
00:05:03,561 --> 00:05:06,881
<i>Soaring effortlessly
on the gentle trade winds,</i>

32
00:05:06,961 --> 00:05:10,521
<i>they can scan vast tracts
of ocean for food.</i>

33
00:05:13,441 --> 00:05:17,601
<i>Frigates must be so lightweight
that they can't afford the heavy oils</i>

34
00:05:17,681 --> 00:05:20,841
<i>that waterproof the plumage
of other sea birds.</i>

35
00:05:21,521 --> 00:05:24,041
<i>So getting wet would be lethal.</i>

36
00:05:25,761 --> 00:05:30,121
<i>This may seem an impossible limitation
for a seafaring hunter.</i>

37
00:05:30,201 --> 00:05:34,881
<i>But frigate birds overcome this handicap
with help from others.</i>

38
00:05:43,321 --> 00:05:44,521
<i>Dorado.</i>

39
00:05:46,041 --> 00:05:49,961
<i>One of the fastest
and most voracious of ocean predators.</i>

40
00:05:52,921 --> 00:05:56,521
<i>They patrol close to the surface,
searching for prey.</i>

41
00:06:06,401 --> 00:06:10,441
<i>Little fish try to hide amidst
the undulating swell of the ocean,</i>

42
00:06:10,521 --> 00:06:12,481
<i>the only cover there is.</i>

43
00:06:19,481 --> 00:06:21,641
<i>It's a game of hide and seek</i>

44
00:06:21,721 --> 00:06:23,961
<i>played out amongst the waves.</i>

45
00:06:27,841 --> 00:06:29,521
<i>Their cover blown,</i>

46
00:06:31,521 --> 00:06:33,561
<i>escape seems impossible.</i>

47
00:06:42,401 --> 00:06:45,601
<i>But these particular fish
have a unique ability.</i>

48
00:07:00,161 --> 00:07:02,321
<i>They're flying fish.</i>

49
00:07:24,801 --> 00:07:27,241
<i>With an extra thrust from their tails,</i>

50
00:07:27,321 --> 00:07:29,681
<i>the flying fish get airborne
once more.</i>

51
00:07:38,321 --> 00:07:42,161
<i>With a good wind,
they can glide for hundreds of metres.</i>

52
00:07:59,641 --> 00:08:03,481
<i>But this is just what the frigate birds
have been waiting for.</i>

53
00:08:07,961 --> 00:08:09,521
<i>When frigates join the hunt,</i>

54
00:08:09,601 --> 00:08:13,761
<i>the flying fish are literally
caught between the devil</i>

55
00:08:15,801 --> 00:08:17,801
<i>and the deep blue sea.</i>

56
00:08:37,241 --> 00:08:39,841
<i>If the flying fish get too much lift</i>

57
00:08:39,921 --> 00:08:42,241
<i>they become easy prey for the frigates.</i>

58
00:08:57,241 --> 00:09:00,401
<i>If they dive to evade attack from above,</i>

59
00:09:05,121 --> 00:09:08,041
<i>they could fall into the mouths
of the dorado.</i>

60
00:09:49,001 --> 00:09:50,961
<i>With the help of the dorado</i>

61
00:09:51,041 --> 00:09:55,321
<i>the wily frigate bird has
become a flying fish specialist,</i>

62
00:09:56,441 --> 00:09:59,281
<i>and without getting
a single feather wet.</i>

63
00:10:05,721 --> 00:10:10,481
<i>Not all open ocean hunters are able
to travel in search of their food...</i>

64
00:10:12,241 --> 00:10:16,841
<i>Some have no choice,
but wait for a meal to come to them.</i>

65
00:10:21,001 --> 00:10:23,281
<i>A mat of sargassum weed</i>

66
00:10:23,361 --> 00:10:25,961
<i>drifts in the middle of the Atlantic.</i>

67
00:10:31,601 --> 00:10:35,961
<i>Sargassum is the only seaweed
to live entirely at the surface,</i>

68
00:10:36,841 --> 00:10:39,321
<i>it never attaches to the sea floor.</i>

69
00:10:43,841 --> 00:10:46,161
<i>This floating tangle of fronds</i>

70
00:10:46,241 --> 00:10:49,921
<i>is home to a surprising open
ocean predator.</i>

71
00:10:50,601 --> 00:10:52,801
<i>The sargassum fish.</i>

72
00:10:56,761 --> 00:11:00,201
<i>Every part of his body mimics the weed.</i>

73
00:11:02,641 --> 00:11:05,881
<i>His fins are more suited
to walking than swimming.</i>

74
00:11:07,841 --> 00:11:10,521
<i>In fact, he can barely swim at all.</i>

75
00:11:12,921 --> 00:11:17,961
<i>He will spend his entire life
marooned on this weedy raft.</i>

76
00:11:26,041 --> 00:11:29,281
<i>This sargassum fish must lie in wait</i>

77
00:11:29,361 --> 00:11:32,641
<i>for those seeking shelter
amongst the weed.</i>

78
00:11:44,961 --> 00:11:48,601
<i>Unfortunately,
his mat is empty for now,</i>

79
00:11:50,681 --> 00:11:54,961
<i>but at least he's not wasting
valuable energy searching for food.</i>

80
00:12:01,241 --> 00:12:03,361
<i>In the featureless ocean,</i>

81
00:12:03,441 --> 00:12:07,641
<i>these mats are much sought
after sanctuary for juvenile fish.</i>

82
00:12:24,921 --> 00:12:26,201
<i>At last...</i>

83
00:12:27,041 --> 00:12:30,241
<i>his first opportunity for weeks.</i>

84
00:12:37,081 --> 00:12:38,881
<i>He must get closer.</i>

85
00:12:39,961 --> 00:12:44,921
<i>He can only strike when he's within
a few centimetres of his prey.</i>

86
00:12:55,121 --> 00:12:59,641
<i>Trusting his perfect camouflage,
he hides in the weed.</i>

87
00:13:05,161 --> 00:13:06,441
<i>Patience.</i>

88
00:13:11,881 --> 00:13:13,841
<i>Still not close enough.</i>

89
00:13:25,481 --> 00:13:28,361
<i>Hunger is clearly getting
the better of him.</i>

90
00:13:41,241 --> 00:13:43,321
<i>Surely this time.</i>

91
00:13:47,361 --> 00:13:48,681
<i>Blown it.</i>

92
00:13:51,041 --> 00:13:54,121
<i>It may be weeks
before he gets another chance.</i>

93
00:14:09,281 --> 00:14:12,041
<i>The open ocean is so vast</i>

94
00:14:12,121 --> 00:14:15,001
<i>that some hunters
can only find enough prey</i>

95
00:14:15,081 --> 00:14:17,041
<i>by searching as a team.</i>

96
00:14:31,281 --> 00:14:35,881
<i>Dolphins live in highly sophisticated
social groups.</i>

97
00:14:44,561 --> 00:14:48,921
<i>Working together they can cover
a huge area of ocean.</i>

98
00:14:53,441 --> 00:14:56,561
<i>These are spinner dolphins.</i>

99
00:14:58,361 --> 00:15:01,921
<i>Why they make these twisting leaps
is still debatable.</i>

100
00:15:02,041 --> 00:15:04,641
<i>Perhaps it's a form of communication.</i>

101
00:15:08,481 --> 00:15:10,961
<i>Or perhaps it’s just fun.</i>

102
00:15:12,961 --> 00:15:15,321
<i>Small groups sometimes come together,</i>

103
00:15:15,401 --> 00:15:18,841
<i>forming super-pods
five thousand strong.</i>

104
00:15:25,361 --> 00:15:28,001
<i>And these are on the hunt.</i>

105
00:15:36,921 --> 00:15:41,121
<i>Spinners are the most vocal
of all the dolphins.</i>

106
00:15:43,921 --> 00:15:46,881
<i>They use echolocation, a kind of sonar,</i>

107
00:15:46,961 --> 00:15:48,681
<i>to find their prey.</i>

108
00:15:49,801 --> 00:15:53,201
<i>Each hunter sends out a series of clicks</i>

109
00:15:54,241 --> 00:15:56,881
<i>and then listens for returning echoes.</i>

110
00:15:59,561 --> 00:16:03,601
<i>Allowing them to scan for distant prey,
hundreds of metres away.</i>

111
00:16:10,161 --> 00:16:13,521
<i>The super-pod spreads out
into a wide hunting line</i>

112
00:16:13,601 --> 00:16:15,401
<i>up to a mile across,</i>

113
00:16:16,721 --> 00:16:19,361
<i>producing a wall of sound.</i>

114
00:16:32,081 --> 00:16:35,161
<i>They're searching
for their favourite prey.</i>

115
00:16:37,761 --> 00:16:39,201
<i>Lantern fish.</i>

116
00:16:39,281 --> 00:16:43,121
<i>They are the most numerous fish
on the planet.</i>

117
00:16:44,681 --> 00:16:49,241
<i>But these small fish spend most of their
time down in the deep ocean,</i>

118
00:16:49,321 --> 00:16:51,721
<i>way beyond the reach of dolphins.</i>

119
00:16:52,801 --> 00:16:55,281
<i>It's only when they come up
to the surface to feed</i>

120
00:16:55,361 --> 00:16:57,201
<i>that they become prey.</i>

121
00:17:00,841 --> 00:17:02,281
<i>Once they've found a shoal</i>

122
00:17:02,361 --> 00:17:05,401
<i>the dolphins use their sonar
in a different way.</i>

123
00:17:07,601 --> 00:17:10,681
<i>They stun the fish with loud blasts,</i>

124
00:17:10,761 --> 00:17:12,841
<i>then simply gather them up.</i>

125
00:17:28,121 --> 00:17:31,761
<i>As they feed, the dolphins work
the underside of the shoal</i>

126
00:17:31,841 --> 00:17:35,921
<i>to stop their prey from escaping
back into the safety of the deep.</i>

127
00:17:56,201 --> 00:18:00,801
<i>Within a few minutes,
all that's left is a shower of scales</i>

128
00:18:00,881 --> 00:18:03,721
<i>drifting downwards to the ocean depths.</i>

129
00:18:16,241 --> 00:18:22,321
<i>The deep ocean is by far the largest
habitat for life on earth.</i>

130
00:18:23,441 --> 00:18:27,481
<i>And home to some of the most
bizarre hunters of all.</i>

131
00:18:31,161 --> 00:18:35,201
<i>Down here, food is much scarcer
than at the surface,</i>

132
00:18:35,281 --> 00:18:38,321
<i>so deep-sea predators
must do all they can</i>

133
00:18:38,401 --> 00:18:40,361
<i>to save precious energy.</i>

134
00:18:49,841 --> 00:18:53,161
<i>Waiting patiently, a viper fish,</i>

135
00:18:53,561 --> 00:18:56,361
<i>special light-producing organs
on its head</i>

136
00:18:57,121 --> 00:18:59,721
<i>entice prey towards fearsome teeth.</i>

137
00:19:04,921 --> 00:19:08,921
<i>Strange, yet deadly,
jelly hunters also live here.</i>

138
00:19:11,601 --> 00:19:13,481
<i>Most simply drift,</i>

139
00:19:13,561 --> 00:19:17,281
<i>trailing tentacles
loaded with lethal stings.</i>

140
00:19:22,921 --> 00:19:26,441
<i>Others, propelled by lines
of beating hairs,</i>

141
00:19:26,521 --> 00:19:28,921
<i>glide gently through the darkness.</i>

142
00:19:44,361 --> 00:19:48,841
<i>Beroe, the top deep-sea jelly predator.</i>

143
00:19:55,161 --> 00:19:57,841
<i>They actively hunt other jellies.</i>

144
00:20:00,361 --> 00:20:02,121
<i>Like this ctenophore.</i>

145
00:20:16,641 --> 00:20:19,521
<i>To grasp its gelatinous prey,</i>

146
00:20:19,601 --> 00:20:23,521
<i>beroe has special teeth-like
spikes in its mouth.</i>

147
00:20:38,361 --> 00:20:42,721
<i>Many deep-sea hunters
just hang in the abyss,</i>

148
00:20:43,321 --> 00:20:44,881
<i>saving their energy,</i>

149
00:20:45,721 --> 00:20:48,361
<i>luring their prey to come to them.</i>

150
00:20:54,521 --> 00:20:56,081
<i>Chiroteuthis.</i>

151
00:20:57,601 --> 00:21:03,361
<i>This deep-sea squid fishes for prey
using long sticky tentacles.</i>

152
00:21:03,881 --> 00:21:05,921
<i>Each has a glowing lure</i>

153
00:21:06,001 --> 00:21:08,921
<i>pulsing to attract passing prey.</i>

154
00:21:25,481 --> 00:21:30,161
<i>A gentle twitch adds to the temptation.</i>

155
00:21:57,601 --> 00:22:02,681
<i>Down here in the darkness
this meal is a rare bonanza.</i>

156
00:22:10,921 --> 00:22:14,761
<i>The open ocean may be
a vast blue desert,</i>

157
00:22:16,361 --> 00:22:20,001
<i>but like all deserts it has oases.</i>

158
00:22:28,081 --> 00:22:31,601
<i>Scattered widely
across this endless space</i>

159
00:22:31,681 --> 00:22:33,961
<i>are thousands of small islands.</i>

160
00:22:38,721 --> 00:22:41,881
<i>These are the summits
of underwater mountains,</i>

161
00:22:41,961 --> 00:22:45,481
<i>which rise up from the sea floor
many miles below.</i>

162
00:22:52,841 --> 00:22:56,721
<i>The sea mounts deflect deep
ocean currents upwards,</i>

163
00:22:56,801 --> 00:22:59,681
<i>forcing nutrient laden water
to the surface.</i>

164
00:23:07,321 --> 00:23:11,601
<i>A busy oasis in the emptiness
of the big blue.</i>

165
00:23:32,561 --> 00:23:35,641
<i>For potential prey
there's plenty of shelter</i>

166
00:23:35,721 --> 00:23:37,401
<i>amongst the coral.</i>

167
00:23:38,921 --> 00:23:42,521
<i>And in the caves that are hidden
beneath the reef itself.</i>

168
00:23:53,561 --> 00:23:55,801
<i>Small fish take refuge here,</i>

169
00:23:55,881 --> 00:23:58,361
<i>out of the reach
of most of their predators.</i>

170
00:24:01,041 --> 00:24:02,441
<i>But not all.</i>

171
00:24:04,521 --> 00:24:05,801
<i>Lion fish.</i>

172
00:24:11,641 --> 00:24:13,801
<i>They're not built for speed...</i>

173
00:24:13,881 --> 00:24:17,601
<i>Success here depends on
delicate maneuvering.</i>

174
00:24:19,761 --> 00:24:23,161
<i>Their strategy is to hide
in plain sight,</i>

175
00:24:23,241 --> 00:24:26,841
<i>lulling their prey
into a false sense of security.</i>

176
00:24:34,721 --> 00:24:37,521
<i>The lion fish’s stripes
are visually confusing,</i>

177
00:24:37,601 --> 00:24:41,361
<i>making it difficult for their prey
to judge how close it is.</i>

178
00:24:55,281 --> 00:24:57,841
<i>Using its extravagant fins</i>

179
00:24:57,921 --> 00:25:02,121
<i>to hide slow and deliberate
tail movements,</i>

180
00:25:02,201 --> 00:25:04,001
<i>it edges ever closer.</i>

181
00:25:08,641 --> 00:25:11,121
<i>It must get to within a few centimetres,</i>

182
00:25:11,201 --> 00:25:13,601
<i>close enough for a sudden strike.</i>

183
00:25:26,161 --> 00:25:27,401
<i>Got one.</i>

184
00:25:38,761 --> 00:25:42,401
<i>The deep-water currents
that sustain so many residents</i>

185
00:25:42,481 --> 00:25:45,521
<i>also attract visitors to these oases.</i>

186
00:25:50,841 --> 00:25:52,521
<i>Silky sharks.</i>

187
00:25:57,321 --> 00:26:00,561
<i>They journey hundreds of miles
between sea mounts,</i>

188
00:26:00,641 --> 00:26:04,161
<i>using them as gathering places
in the featureless ocean.</i>

189
00:26:10,721 --> 00:26:13,001
<i>They’re joined by hammerheads.</i>

190
00:26:17,841 --> 00:26:21,601
<i>Both these sharks constantly
travel between the Galápagos</i>

191
00:26:21,681 --> 00:26:25,241
<i>and other isolated sea mounts
in the Eastern Pacific.</i>

192
00:26:31,161 --> 00:26:34,601
<i>No one knows for sure why they
gather in such numbers,</i>

193
00:26:35,361 --> 00:26:38,961
<i>but some certainly come
to these oases in search of food.</i>

194
00:26:47,001 --> 00:26:51,441
<i>A school of resident silver sides
cloaks the sea mount.</i>

195
00:26:53,161 --> 00:26:55,721
<i>If these little fish
stay close to the coral</i>

196
00:26:55,801 --> 00:26:58,201
<i>the sharks won't be able to get at them.</i>

197
00:27:18,081 --> 00:27:22,841
<i>Other more agile visitors are attracted
by the potential feast.</i>

198
00:27:25,481 --> 00:27:27,081
<i>Striped bonito.</i>

199
00:27:29,081 --> 00:27:30,881
<i>And golden trevally.</i>

200
00:27:37,281 --> 00:27:41,441
<i>To get a meal they'll need to drive
their prey up and away from the reef</i>

201
00:27:41,521 --> 00:27:43,121
<i>into open water.</i>

202
00:27:45,921 --> 00:27:49,521
<i>As long as the silver sides
stick close to the sea floor</i>

203
00:27:49,601 --> 00:27:51,801
<i>they should evade their predators.</i>

204
00:28:13,481 --> 00:28:17,721
<i>This time the frustrated hunters
will have to search elsewhere.</i>

205
00:28:17,801 --> 00:28:21,361
<i>There's never an easy meal
in the open ocean.</i>

206
00:28:34,561 --> 00:28:37,881
<i>The Southern Ocean,
encircling Antarctica...</i>

207
00:28:43,001 --> 00:28:45,321
<i>The wildest seas on our planet.</i>

208
00:28:48,041 --> 00:28:53,001
<i>Here, it's these storm-tossed waters
that bring nutrients to the surface,</i>

209
00:28:53,081 --> 00:28:55,721
<i>creating isolated patches of richness.</i>

210
00:28:58,681 --> 00:29:00,561
<i>Far from the calm tropics,</i>

211
00:29:00,641 --> 00:29:04,601
<i>this weather-beaten ocean
is home to the albatross.</i>

212
00:29:13,201 --> 00:29:15,001
<i>Black browed albatross</i>

213
00:29:15,081 --> 00:29:17,441
<i>are the same size as frigate birds,</i>

214
00:29:17,521 --> 00:29:19,401
<i>but three times as heavy,</i>

215
00:29:19,481 --> 00:29:22,921
<i>and so they need
a totally different flying technique.</i>

216
00:29:27,561 --> 00:29:32,041
<i>Albatross have the longest wingspan
of any bird</i>

217
00:29:32,121 --> 00:29:36,801
<i>and that enables them to exploit
the power of the Southern Ocean winds.</i>

218
00:29:40,841 --> 00:29:43,361
<i>First, they glide into the wind,</i>

219
00:29:43,441 --> 00:29:46,201
<i>harnessing its energy to give them lift.</i>

220
00:29:49,201 --> 00:29:53,361
<i>Then they turn and descend downwind,
